english:
  title: Postscript to the Record of the Hall of Bamboo
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: "The noble and refined gentleman, flowing with elegance and brilliance, yet lacking the transcendent thought to rise above worldly dust—he loves only exotic flowers and rare trees. The bamboo's pure and austere beauty he regards as common. So too with men: he cherishes only the flattering and ingratiating sort, while the steadfast and upright scholar wins his affection merely in passing. I know that floating blossoms and drifting stamens share the same essence as honeyed words and painted smiles. What pleases the eye and ear comes easily; what moves the heart runs deep. Thus the lovers of such things are legion—not merely the elegant and refined. \n\nConsider the frost-touched stems and snow-laden joints, the wind-bent branches and rain-washed leaves—these are bamboo's loveliness. Righteousness, sincerity, steadfastness, unbending resolve—these are what the gentleman ought to honor. Yet the world abandons these and loves only that. The compliant and the defiant make poor companions; the gentleman must know what to choose.\n\nWhen myriad blossoms compete in beauty and fragrant mists drift softly, all seems pleasant, all worthy of admiration—until wind and rain suddenly bring ruin. Such is their nature. But when bitter cold arrives, the bamboo's noble bearing shines forth, revealing what sets it apart from common wood. When men pursue profit and power, bend their will and compromise their integrity, flowing with the current like water—such is the path they share. Yet the noble and unbound—this is what distinguishes the gentleman from the common mass. He who abandons the former to love only the latter must stand upon firm ground, see from great heights, possess something he guards and cannot be deceived about.\n\nThis lord, of royal lineage and worthy of the people's trust, wielding authority over a province, positioned above the highest ministers—he has known many men and savored much in this world. Yet he loves only bamboo. He planted it throughout his courtyard and grounds, gave his hall the name \"Bamboo Hall,\" and at dawn's breeze and evening's moon he faces it, chanting verse in clear tones, content and self-satisfied, forgetting both wealth and rank. Ah, this is indeed worthy of honor! Observe what he honors, examine what he preserves, and you know his beloved must be the upright and incorruptible scholar. Those flattering sycophants shall never ascend his hall.\n\nThe Record says: \"To assess a man, look to his companions.\" So I venture to compare what the gentleman preserves with the bamboo, and present this to him. What say you? If one objects that what we honor need not be what we embody—then that exceeds what I dare claim to know. As for the hall's refined charm, my colleagues' verses have already captured it fully. I merely add these humble words as a postscript."
  footnotes:
    - The Hall of Bamboo (竹堂) refers to a study or residence named after the owner's love of bamboo, often a retreat for scholarly pursuits and moral cultivation.
    - The phrase 'frost-touched stems and snow-laden joints' (霜莖雪節) uses winter imagery to represent bamboo's resilience and purity—virtues valued in Confucian thought.
    - Lee Cham employs a sophisticated parallel structure comparing bamboo's constancy to human virtue, a common rhetorical device in Korean literati writing of the Joseon period.
